$CATEGORY: top/Healthcare Foundations/Medicare vs. Medicaid

::Q-CON-001:: Medicare eligibility is based mainly on age (65 and older), while Medicaid eligibility is based mainly on income. {TRUE #### Medicare is primarily for people 65+, whereas Medicaid eligibility is based on income and household size.}

::Q-CON-002:: Medicaid is primarily intended for people with low income. {TRUE #### Medicaid provides health coverage to eligible low-income adults, children, pregnant women, elderly adults, and people with disabilities.}

::Q-CON-003:: Medicare's basic rules are set separately by each individual state. {FALSE #### Medicare is a purely federal program administered nationwide by CMS, so its basic rules are the same in every state.}

::Q-CON-004:: Medicaid is funded jointly by the federal government and the states. {TRUE #### Medicaid is a joint federal-state program; the federal share is set by the Federal Medical Assistance Percentage (FMAP).}

::Q-CON-005:: Medicare is administered nationwide by CMS, a federal agency within HHS. {TRUE #### Medicare is administered by the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS), a federal agency within HHS.}

::Q-CON-006:: Original Medicare is the main program that pays for long-term nursing home (custodial) care. {FALSE #### Medicaid, not Medicare, is the primary payer for long-term services and supports; Original Medicare generally does not cover long-term custodial care.}

::Q-CON-007:: Medicaid is the primary payer for long-term services and supports in the United States. {TRUE #### Medicaid is the nation's primary payer for long-term services and supports (LTSS), including nursing home care.}

::Q-CON-008:: Parts A, B, C, and D are all parts of Medicare. {TRUE #### Medicare has four parts: A (hospital), B (medical), C (Medicare Advantage), and D (prescription drugs).}

::Q-CON-009:: Medicaid is divided into Part A and Part B, just like Medicare. {FALSE #### Medicaid does not use the lettered Part A/B/C/D structure; that structure belongs to Medicare. Medicaid's companion program for children is CHIP.}

::Q-CON-010:: Medicare Part C (Medicare Advantage) plans are offered by private companies approved by Medicare. {TRUE #### Medicare Advantage (Part C) is an alternative to Original Medicare offered by Medicare-approved private companies.}

::Q-CON-011:: CHIP provides low-cost health coverage to children. {TRUE #### The Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP) provides low-cost coverage to children in families that earn too much for Medicaid but cannot afford private insurance.}

::Q-CON-012:: A person can be enrolled in both Medicare and Medicaid at the same time. {TRUE #### People enrolled in both programs are called 'dually eligible' individuals, so a person can have both at once.}

::Q-CON-013:: For someone enrolled in both programs, Medicaid pays first and Medicare pays last. {FALSE #### For dual eligibles, Medicare pays first for services it covers and Medicaid is generally the payer of last resort.}

::Q-CON-014:: Medicare Part B requires a monthly premium. {TRUE #### Medicare Part B (Medical Insurance) requires a monthly premium; for 2026 the standard premium is $202.90.}

::Q-CON-015:: Because Medicaid is run by the states, eligibility and covered benefits can vary from state to state. {TRUE #### Each state administers its own Medicaid program within federal rules, so eligibility details and benefits can vary by state.}

::Q-CON-016:: Which program is primarily for people age 65 and older? {
=Medicare #Medicare is the federal program primarily for people age 65 and older.
~Medicaid #Medicaid is based on income, not age.
~CHIP #CHIP covers children, not seniors.
~The Health Insurance Marketplace #The Marketplace sells private plans; it is not an age-based program.
}

::Q-CON-017:: Which program bases eligibility mainly on a person's income? {
~Medicare #Medicare is based mainly on age, not income.
=Medicaid #Medicaid eligibility is based mainly on income and household size.
~Medicare Part C #Part C is a way to receive Medicare benefits, still age-based.
~Medicare Part D #Part D is Medicare drug coverage, still age-based.
}

::Q-CON-018:: Which statement best describes how the two programs are administered? {
~Both are purely federal and uniform nationwide #Only Medicare is uniform; Medicaid varies by state.
~Both are run entirely by the states #Medicare is federal, not state-run.
=Medicare is federal and uniform; Medicaid is state-run and varies by state #Medicare is administered federally by CMS (uniform nationwide), while Medicaid is administered by each state within federal rules (so it varies).
~Medicare is state-run; Medicaid is purely federal #This reverses the two programs.
}

::Q-CON-019:: How is Medicaid funded? {
~Entirely by the federal government #Medicaid funding is shared, not purely federal; Medicare is the purely federal program.
~Entirely by state governments #States share the cost with the federal government, not alone.
~Entirely by employer premiums #Employer premiums fund commercial insurance, not Medicaid.
=Jointly by the federal government and the states #Medicaid is funded jointly by the federal government and the states, with the federal share set by the FMAP.
}

::Q-CON-020:: Which agency administers Medicare across the country? {
=The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS) #Medicare is administered nationwide by CMS, a federal agency within HHS.
~Each state's health department #States administer Medicaid, not Medicare.
~The Internal Revenue Service (IRS) #The IRS handles taxes, not Medicare administration.
~Private insurance companies acting alone #Private companies offer some plans but do not administer the federal program.
}

::Q-CON-021:: Which program is the main payer for long-term nursing home care in the U.S.? {
~Medicare #Original Medicare generally does not cover long-term custodial care.
=Medicaid #Medicaid is the nation's primary payer for long-term services and supports, including nursing home care.
~CHIP #CHIP covers children, not long-term care.
~Commercial insurance #Commercial plans rarely cover extended long-term care.
}

::Q-CON-022:: A patient needs several years of custodial nursing-home care. Which program is most likely to pay for it? {
~Medicare Part A #Part A covers short inpatient hospital stays, not long-term custodial care.
~Medicare Part B #Part B covers outpatient and doctor services, not long-term care.
=Medicaid #Long-term custodial care is generally paid by Medicaid, the primary payer for long-term services and supports.
~Medicare Part D #Part D covers prescription drugs, not long-term care.
}

::Q-CON-023:: Which list correctly names the four parts of Medicare? {
~Part 1, Part 2, Part 3, Part 4 #Medicare parts are lettered, not numbered.
~Part A and Part B only #A and B are only Original Medicare; C and D also exist.
~Part A, Part B, Part C, Part D, and Part E #There is no Part E.
=Part A, Part B, Part C, Part D #Medicare has four parts: A, B, C, and D.
}

::Q-CON-024:: Medicare Part C is also known by what name? {
=Medicare Advantage #Medicare Part C is also called Medicare Advantage, offered by Medicare-approved private companies.
~Medigap #Medigap is separate supplemental insurance, not Part C.
~Medicaid #Medicaid is a different program entirely.
~CHIP #CHIP is the children's program on the Medicaid side.
}

::Q-CON-025:: What does Medicare Part D cover? {
~Inpatient hospital stays #Inpatient hospital care is Part A.
=Prescription drugs #Medicare Part D is optional prescription drug coverage offered through private companies approved by Medicare.
~Long-term nursing home care #Long-term care is mainly covered by Medicaid.
~Doctor office visits #Doctor visits are Part B.
}

::Q-CON-026:: Which statement about Medicaid's structure is correct? {
~Medicaid is divided into Parts A, B, C, and D like Medicare #Lettered parts belong to Medicare, not Medicaid.
~Medicaid only covers prescription drugs #Medicaid covers a broad range of services, not only drugs.
=Medicaid has no lettered parts and pairs with CHIP for children #Medicaid does not use lettered parts; its companion program for children is CHIP.
~Medicaid is identical to Medicare #The two programs differ in eligibility, funding, and structure.
}

::Q-CON-027:: Whom does CHIP primarily cover? {
~Adults age 65 and older #Seniors are served by Medicare, not CHIP.
~Military veterans #Veterans have separate VA coverage.
~Large employers #CHIP covers children, not employers.
=Children in families that earn too much for Medicaid but cannot afford private insurance #CHIP provides low-cost coverage to children in families earning too much for Medicaid but unable to afford private insurance.
}

::Q-CON-028:: Which statement about cost is true? {
=Medicare Part B has a monthly premium #Medicare Part B requires a monthly premium ($202.90 in 2026), plus deductibles and coinsurance for many services.
~Medicare is always completely free #Medicare usually involves some cost, such as the Part B premium.
~Medicare never charges any premiums #Part B does charge a premium.
~Only Medicaid charges premiums #Medicare, not Medicaid, is the program with regular premiums.
}

::Q-CON-029:: For a person with very low income, which program typically costs the patient little or nothing? {
~Medicare #Medicare usually involves premiums and cost-sharing.
=Medicaid #Medicaid is designed for people with limited income and generally costs the beneficiary little or nothing.
~A commercial PPO plan #Commercial plans charge premiums.
~Medicare Part C #Part C is a Medicare option and can involve costs.
}

::Q-CON-030:: People who are enrolled in both Medicare and Medicaid at the same time are called what? {
~Dependents #A dependent is a person covered under another's plan.
~Subscribers #A subscriber is the primary policyholder of one plan.
=Dual eligibles #People enrolled in both Medicare and Medicaid are called dually eligible (or dual eligible) individuals.
~Self-pay patients #Self-pay patients have no insurance coverage.
}

::Q-CON-031:: For a dual-eligible person, which program pays first for a covered service? {
~Medicaid #Medicaid is generally the payer of last resort, paying after Medicare.
~CHIP #CHIP covers children, not dual-eligible adults.
~The patient pays first #Coverage pays before the patient is billed for covered services.
=Medicare #For dual eligibles, Medicare pays first for services it covers.
}

::Q-CON-032:: The phrase 'payer of last resort' for dual eligibles refers to which program? {
=Medicaid #Medicaid is generally the payer of last resort, paying after Medicare and other coverage.
~Medicare #Medicare pays first, not last.
~Commercial insurance #Commercial insurance is not the dual-eligible context here.
~CHIP #CHIP is the children's program, not the last-resort payer.
}

::Q-CON-033:: For dual eligibles, Medicaid often helps pay which Medicare costs? {
~Nothing at all #Medicaid does help with Medicare costs for dual eligibles.
=Medicare premiums and cost-sharing #For dually eligible individuals, Medicaid helps pay Medicare premiums and cost-sharing and covers gaps like long-term care.
~Only prescriptions bought outside the U.S. #Medicaid's help is not limited to drugs purchased abroad.
~Hospital meal charges only #Medicaid's assistance is far broader than meal charges.
}

::Q-CON-034:: Which statement correctly contrasts the two programs? {
~Medicare is income-based; Medicaid is age-based #This reverses the two programs.
~Both are age-based #Only Medicare is age-based.
=Medicare is age-based; Medicaid is income-based #Medicare is based mainly on age (65+), while Medicaid is based mainly on income.
~Both are income-based #Only Medicaid is income-based.
}

::Q-CON-035:: A financially well-off 70-year-old retiree is generally eligible for which program? {
~Medicaid #Medicaid is income-based; a well-off person generally would not qualify.
~CHIP #CHIP is for children.
~Neither program #Age 65+ qualifies a person for Medicare.
=Medicare #Medicare eligibility is based on age, so a 70-year-old qualifies regardless of income.
}

::Q-CON-036:: A low-income 30-year-old parent with little income might qualify for which program? {
=Medicaid #Medicaid is income-based, so a low-income adult may qualify even though they are far from age 65.
~Medicare #Medicare is mainly for people 65+ or with certain disabilities.
~Medicare Part B #Part B is a component of Medicare, still age-based.
~Medicare Advantage #Medicare Advantage is a Medicare option, still age-based.
}

::Q-CON-037:: A Medicare Advantage (Part C) plan typically bundles which coverage together? {
~Only Part A #Advantage plans include more than just Part A.
=Part A, Part B, and usually Part D #Medicare Advantage plans are bundled and include Part A and Part B and usually Part D drug coverage.
~Only prescription drugs #Drug coverage is usually included but is not the whole plan.
~Only long-term care #Long-term care is generally a Medicaid responsibility.
}

::Q-CON-038:: Why can Medicaid benefits differ depending on the state you live in? {
~Because Medicaid is federally uniform #Medicaid is not federally uniform; that describes Medicare.
~Because hospitals set Medicaid rules #States, not individual hospitals, run Medicaid.
=Because each state runs its own Medicaid program within federal rules #Each state administers its own Medicaid program within federal requirements, so eligibility and benefits can vary.
~Because benefits are priced by ZIP code #Variation comes from state administration, not ZIP-code pricing.
}

::Q-CON-039:: Which program has essentially the same basic rules in every state? {
~Medicaid #Medicaid varies by state.
~CHIP #CHIP is state-administered and varies.
~Employer-sponsored insurance #Employer plans differ by employer.
=Medicare #Medicare is federally administered by CMS, so its basic rules are uniform nationwide.
}

::Q-CON-040:: Which is a key difference in what the two programs cover? {
=Medicaid, not Medicare, is the main payer for long-term care #Both cover doctors and hospitals, but Medicaid is the primary payer for long-term care, which Original Medicare generally does not cover.
~Only Medicare covers doctor visits #Both programs cover doctor visits.
~Only Medicaid covers hospital stays #Both programs cover hospital care.
~Neither program covers preventive care #Both cover preventive services.
}

